definition.value: A monohydroxyflavone that is the 3-hydroxy derivative of flavone.
An agent which regulates the physiologic mechanisms that control the appetite and food intake.

An EC 1.3.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on CH-CH group of donor, NAD(+) or NADP(+) as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of of 3-oxo-5alpha-steroid 4-dehydrogenase (NADP(+)), EC 1.3.1.22, the enzyme which converts testosterone (CHEBI:17347) into the more potent androgen 5alpha-dihydrotestosterone.
A carboxylic ester of pivalic acid.

A steroid hormone related to the hormone testosterone. It increases protein synthesis within cells, which results in the buildup of cellular tissue (anabolism), especially in muscles. It also has androgenic and virilizing properties.

An EC 1.1.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) acceptor) inhibitor which interferes with the action of 3beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase (EC 1.1.1.210), a group of steroidogenic enzymes.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is the (3S)-hydroxy-derivative of L-asparagine.

An EC 1.14.14.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, incorporating of 1 atom of oxygen, with reduced flavin or flavoprotein as one donor) inhibitor which interferes with the action of aromatase (EC 1.14.14.14) and so reduces production of estrogenic steroid hormones.
An antagonist at the estrogen receptor.
A nanometre sized object.
A nanometre sized tube composed of either organic or inorganic substances.
A carbon nanotube consisting of two concentric graphene cylinders.
A single-walled carbon nanotube with equal n and m indices. Armchair carbon nanotubes have a chiral angle of 30degree and are metallic.
A single walled carbon nanotube with (n,m) indices equal to (n,0) or (0,m). Zigzag carbon nanotubes have a chiral angle of 0degree and can be either metallic or semiconducting.
An epoxide that is oxirane substituted by a (4-nitrophenoxy)methyl group.
A single-walled carbon nanotube with unequal (n,m) indices and a chiral angle of between 0 and 30degree.
A single-walled carbon nanotube with (n,m) indices such that n-m is a multiple of 3.
A single-walled carbon nanotube with (n,m) indices such that n-m is not a multiple of 3.
A nanosized spherical or capsule-shaped structure.
A nanoparticle composed of a metallic shell (e.g. gold) surrounding a semiconductor (e.g. silicon).
A nanoscale rod composed of either metallic or semiconducting material or a mixture of both.
A hollow shell consisting of covalently cross-linked carbon nanotubes.
A nanostructure produced by filling the hollow cavity of a carbon nanotube with different substance.
A carbon nanotube grown in a nitrogen-rich atmosphere, in which a small percentage of carbon atoms have been replaced by nitrogen atoms.
Carbon nanotubes grown in a boron-rich atmosphere, in which a small percentage of carbon atoms have been replaced by boron atoms.
A carbon nanotube grown in a boron- and nitrogen-rich atmosphere in which some of the carbon atoms have been replaced by B and N atoms in the order C > B > N.
A single-walled carbon nanostructure with an irregular horn-like shape.
A carbon nanostructure consisting of carbon nanotubes which have been spun or bundled together.
A carbon nanostructure consisting of layers of stacked graphite cones or plates.
A nanoparticle consisting of an iron oxide.
A nanoparticle consisting of magnetite, Fe(2+)Fe(3+)2O4.
An iron oxide nanoparticle composed of hematite (Fe2O3).
A nanoparticle consisting of gold atoms.
A nanoparticle consisting of silver atoms.
A drug used to treat hyperparathyroidism by reducing the excessive production of parathyroid hormones.
